same arguments as the command line tool:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eurl_list\u003c/strong\u003e A file with the list of url of images to download. It can be a folder of such files. (\u003cem\u003erequired\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eimage_size\u003c/strong\u003e The size to resize image to (default \u003cem\u003e256\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eoutput_folder\u003c/strong\u003e The path to the output folder. (default \u003cem\u003e\"images\"\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eprocesses_count\u003c/strong\u003e The number of processes used for downloading the pictures. This is important to be high for performance. (default \u003cem\u003e1\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ethread_count\u003c/strong\u003e The number of threads used for downloading the pictures. This is important to be high for performance. (default \u003cem\u003e256\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eresize_mode\u003c/strong\u003e The way to resize pictures, can be no, border or keep_ratio (default \u003cem\u003eborder\u003c/em\u003e)\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eno\u003c/strong\u003e doesn't resize at all\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eborder\u003c/strong\u003e will make the image image_size x image_size and add a border\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ekeep_ratio\u003c/strong\u003e will keep the ratio and make the smallest side of the picture image_size\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ekeep_ratio_largest\u003c/strong\u003e will keep the ratio and make the largest side of the picture image_size\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ecenter_crop\u003c/strong\u003e will keep the ratio and center crop the largest side so the picture is squared\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eresize_only_if_bigger\u003c/strong\u003e resize pictures only if bigger that the image_size (default \u003cem\u003eFalse\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eupscale_interpolation\u003c/strong\u003e kind of upscale interpolation used for resizing (default \u003cem\u003e\"lanczos\"\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003edownscale_interpolation\u003c/strong\u003e kind of downscale interpolation used for resizing (default \u003cem\u003e\"area\"\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eencode_quality\u003c/strong\u003e encode quality from 0 to 100, when using png it is the compression factor from 0 to 9 (default \u003cem\u003e95\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eencode_format\u003c/strong\u003e encode format (default \u003cem\u003ejpg\u003c/em\u003e)\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ejpg\u003c/strong\u003e jpeg format\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003epng\u003c/strong\u003e png format\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ewebp\u003c/strong\u003e webp format\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eskip_reencode\u003c/strong\u003e whether to skip reencoding if no resizing is done (default \u003cem\u003eFalse\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eoutput_format\u003c/strong\u003e decides how to save pictures (default \u003cem\u003efiles\u003c/em\u003e)\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003efiles\u003c/strong\u003e saves as a set of subfolder containing pictures\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ewebdataset\u003c/strong\u003e saves as tars containing pictures\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eparquet\u003c/strong\u003e saves as parquet containing pictures as bytes\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003etfrecord\u003c/strong\u003e saves as tfrecord containing pictures as bytes\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003edummy\u003c/strong\u003e does not save. Useful for benchmarks\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003einput_format\u003c/strong\u003e decides how to load the urls (default \u003cem\u003etxt\u003c/em\u003e)\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003etxt\u003c/strong\u003e loads the urls as a text file of url, one per line\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003etxt.gz\u003c/strong\u003e loads the urls as a compressed (gzip) txt.gz with a list of url, one per line\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ecsv\u003c/strong\u003e loads the urls and optional caption as a csv\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ecsv.gz\u003c/strong\u003e loads the urls and optional caption, as a compressed (gzip) csv.gz\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003etsv\u003c/strong\u003e loads the urls and optional caption as a tsv\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003etsv.gz\u003c/strong\u003e loads the urls and optional caption, as a compressed (gzip) tsv.gz\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ejson\u003c/strong\u003e loads the urls and optional caption as a json\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ejson.gz\u003c/strong\u003e loads the urls and optional caption, as a compressed (gzip) json.gz\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ejsonl\u003c/strong\u003e loads the urls and optional caption as a jsonl. see \u003ca href=\"https://jsonlines.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003ejsonlines\u003c/a\u003e for more\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ejsonl.gz\u003c/strong\u003e loads the urls and optional caption, as a compressed (gzip) jsonl.gz. see \u003ca href=\"https://jsonlines.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003ejsonlines\u003c/a\u003e for more\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eparquet\u003c/strong\u003e loads the urls and optional caption as a parquet\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eurl_col\u003c/strong\u003e the name of the url column for parquet and csv (default \u003cem\u003eurl\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ecaption_col\u003c/strong\u003e the name of the caption column for parquet and csv (default \u003cem\u003eNone\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ebbox_col\u003c/strong\u003e the name of the bounding box column. Bounding boxes are assumed to have format \u003ccode\u003e[x_min, y_min, x_max, y_max]\u003c/code\u003e, with all elements being floats in \u003cem\u003e[0,1]\u003c/em\u003e (relative to the size of the image). If \u003cem\u003eNone\u003c/em\u003e, then no bounding box blurring is performed (default \u003cem\u003eNone\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003enumber_sample_per_shard\u003c/strong\u003e the number of sample that will be downloaded in one shard (default \u003cem\u003e10000\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eextract_exif\u003c/strong\u003e if true, extract the exif information of the images and save it to the metadata (default \u003cem\u003eTrue\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003esave_additional_columns\u003c/strong\u003e list of additional columns to take from the csv/parquet files and save in metadata files (default \u003cem\u003eNone\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003etimeout\u003c/strong\u003e maximum time (in seconds) to wait when trying to download an image (default \u003cem\u003e10\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eenable_wandb\u003c/strong\u003e whether to enable wandb logging (default \u003cem\u003eFalse\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ewandb_project\u003c/strong\u003e name of W\u0026amp;B project used (default \u003cem\u003eimg2dataset\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eoom_shard_count\u003c/strong\u003e the order of magnitude of the number of shards, used only to decide what zero padding to use to name the shard files (default \u003cem\u003e5\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ecompute_hash\u003c/strong\u003e the hash of raw images to compute and store in the metadata, one of \u003cem\u003eNone\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem\u003emd5\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem\u003esha256\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem\u003esha512\u003c/em\u003e (default \u003cem\u003esha256\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003everify_hash\u003c/strong\u003e if not \u003cem\u003eNone\u003c/em\u003e, then this is a list of two elements that will be used to verify hashes based on the provided input. The first element of this list is the label of the column containing the hashes in the input file, while the second one is the type of the hash that is being checked (default \u003cem\u003eNone\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003edistributor\u003c/strong\u003e choose how to distribute the downloading (default \u003cem\u003emultiprocessing\u003c/em\u003e)\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003emultiprocessing\u003c/strong\u003e use a multiprocessing pool to spawn processes\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003epyspark\u003c/strong\u003e use a pyspark session to create workers on a spark cluster (see details below)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eray\u003c/strong\u003e use a ray cluster. See ray example.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003esubjob_size\u003c/strong\u003e the number of shards to download in each subjob supporting it, a subjob can be a pyspark job for example (default \u003cem\u003e1000\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eretries\u003c/strong\u003e number of time a download should be retried (default \u003cem\u003e0\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003edisable_all_reencoding\u003c/strong\u003e if set to True, this will keep the image files in their original state with no resizing and no conversion, will not even check if the image is valid. Useful for benchmarks. To use only if you plan to post process the images by another program and you have plenty of storage available. (default \u003cem\u003eFalse\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003emin_image_size\u003c/strong\u003e minimum size of the image to download (default \u003cem\u003e0\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003emax_image_area\u003c/strong\u003e maximum area of the image to download (default \u003cem\u003einf\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003emax_aspect_ratio\u003c/strong\u003e maximum aspect ratio of the image to download (default \u003cem\u003einf\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eincremental_mode\u003c/strong\u003e Can be \"incremental\", \"overwrite\" or \"extend\". For \"incremental\", img2dataset will download all the shards that were not downloaded, for \"overwrite\" img2dataset will delete recursively the output folder then start from zero, for \"extend\" img2dataset will download shards from the next available shard number (default \u003cem\u003eincremental\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003emax_shard_retry\u003c/strong\u003e Number of time to retry failed shards at the end (default \u003cem\u003e1\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003euser_agent_token\u003c/strong\u003e Additional identifying token that will be added to the User-Agent header sent with HTTP requests to download images; for example: \"img2downloader\". (default \u003cem\u003eNone\u003c/em\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003edisallowed_header_directives\u003c/strong\u003e List of X-Robots-Tags header directives that, if present in HTTP response when downloading an image, will cause the image to be excluded from the output dataset. To ignore x-robots-tags, pass '[]'. (default '[\"noai\", \"noimageai\", \"noindex\", \"noimageindex\"]')\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"markdown-heading\" dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003ch2 tabindex=\"-1\" dir=\"auto\"\u003eImg2dataset support several formats. There are trade off for which to choose:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003efiles: this is the simplest one, images are simply saved as files. It's good for up to 1M samples on a local file system. Beyond that performance issues appear very fast. Handling more than a million files in standard filesystem does not work well.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ewebdataset: webdataset format saves samples in tar files, thanks to \u003ca href=\"https://webdataset.github.io/webdataset/\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003ewebdataset\u003c/a\u003e library, this makes it possible to load the resulting dataset fast in both pytorch, tensorflow and jax. Choose this for most use cases. It works well for any filesystem\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eparquet: parquet is a columnar format that allows fast filtering. It's particularly easy to read it using pyarrow and pyspark. Choose this if the rest of your data ecosystem is based on pyspark. \u003ca href=\"https://github.com/uber/petastorm\"\u003epetastorm\u003c/a\u003e can be used to read the data but it's not as easy to use as webdataset\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003etfrecord: tfrecord is a protobuf based format. It's particularly easy to use from tensorflow and using \u003ca href=\"https://www.tensorflow.org/guide/data\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003etf data\u003c/a\u003e. Use this if you plan to use the dataset only in the tensorflow ecosystem. The tensorflow writer does not use fsspec and as a consequence supports only a limited amount of filesystem, including local, hdfs, s3 and gcs. It is also less efficient than the webdataset writer when writing to other filesystems than local, losing some 30% performance.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"markdown-heading\" with an aspect ratio greater than RATIO\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eWhen filtering data, it is recommended to pre-shuffle your dataset to limit the impact on shard size dataset. For larger ones, these tips may help you get the best performance:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eset the processes_count as the number of cores your machine has\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eincrease thread_count as long as your bandwidth and cpu are below the limits\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eI advise to set output_format to webdataset if your dataset has more than 1M elements, it will be easier to manipulate few tars rather than million of files\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ekeeping metadata to True can be useful to check what items were already saved and avoid redownloading them\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eTo benchmark your system, and img2dataset interactions with it, it may be interesting to enable these options (only for testing, not for real downloads)\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e--output_format dummy : will not save anything. Good to remove the storage bottleneck\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e--disable_all_reencoding True : will not reencode anything. Good to remove the cpu bottleneck\nWhen both these options are enabled, the only bottlenecks left are network related: eg dns setup, your bandwidth or the url servers bandwidth.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"markdown-heading\" dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003ch2 tabindex=\"-1\" class=\"heading-element\" dir=\"auto\"\u003eFile system support\u003c/h2\u003e\u003ca id=\"user-content-file-system-support\" class=\"anchor-element\" aria-label=\"Permalink: File system support\" href=\"#file-system-support\"\u003e\u003csvg class=\"octicon octicon-link\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eThanks to \u003ca href=\"https://filesystem-spec.readthedocs.io/en/latest/\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003efsspec\u003c/a\u003e, img2dataset supports reading and writing files in \u003ca href=\"https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec/blob/6233f315548b512ec379323f762b70764efeb92c/fsspec/registry.py#L87\"\u003emany file systems\u003c/a\u003e.\nTo use it, simply use the prefix of your filesystem before the path. For example \u003ccode\u003ehdfs://\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003es3://\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ehttp://\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003egcs://\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003essh://\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ehf://\u003c/code\u003e (includes a \u003ca href=\"https://huggingface.co/docs/hub/datasets-viewer\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003eDataset Viewer\u003c/a\u003e).\nSome of these file systems require installing an additional package (for example s3fs for s3, gcsfs for gcs, \u003ca href=\"https://github.com/fsspec/sshfs\"\u003efsspec/sshfs\u003c/a\u003e for ssh, \u003ca href=\"https://huggingface.co/docs/huggingface_hub/guides/hf_file_system\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003ehuggingface_hub\u003c/a\u003e for hf).\nSee fsspec doc for all the details.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eIf you need specific configuration for your filesystem, you may handle this problem by using the \u003ca href=\"https://filesystem-spec.readthedocs.io/en/latest/features.html#configuration\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003efsspec configuration system\u003c/a\u003e that makes it possible to create a file such as \u003ccode\u003e.config/fsspec/s3.json\u003c/code\u003e and have information in it such as:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"highlight highlight-source-json \u0026quot;endpoint_url\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;https://some_endpoint\u0026quot;,\n            \u0026quot;aws_access_key_id\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;your_user\u0026quot;,\n Some numbers assuming 1350 image/s:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBandwidth: downloading a thousand average image per second requires about 130MB/s\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCPU: resizing one image may take several milliseconds, several thousand per second can use up to 16 cores\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDNS querying: million of urls mean million of domains, default OS setting usually are not enough. Setting up a local bind9 resolver may be required\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDisk: if using resizing, up to 30MB/s write speed is necessary. If not using resizing, up to 130MB/s. Writing in few tar files make it possible to use rotational drives instead of a SSD.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eWith these information in mind, the design choice was done in this way:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ethe list of urls is split in K shards. K is chosen such that a shard has a reasonable size on disk (for example 256MB), by default K = 10000\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eN processes are started (using multiprocessing process pool)\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eeach process starts M threads. M should be maximized in order to use as much network as possible while keeping cpu usage below 100%.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eeach of this thread download 1 image and returns it\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ethe parent thread handle resizing (which means there is at most N resizing running at once, using up the cores but not more)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ethe parent thread saves to a tar file that is different from other process\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eThis design make it possible to use the CPU resource efficiently by doing only 1 resize per core, reduce disk overhead by opening 1 file per core, while using the bandwidth resource as much as possible by using M thread per process.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eAlso see \u003ca href=\"/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/img2dataset/architecture.md\"\u003earchitecture.md\u003c/a\u003e for the precise split in python modules.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"markdown-heading\" dir=\"auto\"\u003e\u003ch2 tabindex=\"-1\" class=\"heading-element\" dir=\"auto\"\u003eSetting up a high performance dns \u003ccode\u003eoptions\u003c/code\u003e:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"snippet-clipboard-content notranslate position-relative overflow-auto\" /etc/resolv.conf\u003c/pre\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eThis will make it possible to keep an high success rate while doing thousands of dns queries.\nYou may also want to \u003ca cases. Use cases involve:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003edoing inference and indexing to better understand what is in the web (\u003ca href=\"https://rom1504.github.io/clip-retrieval/\" rel=\"nofollow\"\u003ehttps://rom1504.github.io/clip-retrieval/\u003c/a\u003e is an example of this)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003etraining models\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eModels that can be trained using image/text datasets include:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCLIP: an image understanding model that allow for example to know whether an image is safe, aesthetic, what animal it contains, ...\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003etext to image models: generating images based on text\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eThere is a lot of discussions regarding the consequences of text to image models. Some opinions include:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul dir=\"auto\"\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAI art is democratizing art and letting hundred of millions of people express themselves through art. Making art much more prevalent and unique\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAI models should not be trained on images that creator do not want to share\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp dir=\"auto\"\u003eThe opt out directive try to let creators that do not want to share their art not be used for indexing and for training.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"markdown-heading\" dir="auto">Opt-out directives</h2><a id="user-content-opt-out-directives" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Opt-out directives" href="#opt-out-directives"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">Websites can pass the http headers <code>X-Robots-Tag: noai</code>, <code>X-Robots-Tag: noindex</code> , <code>X-Robots-Tag: noimageai</code> and <code>X-Robots-Tag: noimageindex</code>By default img2dataset will ignore images with such headers.</p><p dir="auto">To disable this behavior and download all images, you may pass --disallowed_header_directives '[]'</p><p dir="auto">See <a href="#ai-use-impact">AI use impact</a> to understand better why you may decide to enable or disable this feature.</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Examples</h2><a id="user-content-examples" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Examples" href="#examples"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">Example of datasets to download with example commands are available in the <a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples">dataset_examples</a> folder. In particular:</p><ul dir="auto"><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/mscoco.md">mscoco</a> 600k image/text pairs that can be downloaded in 10min</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/SBUcaptions.md">sbucaptions</a> 860K image/text pairs can be downloaded in 20 mins.</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/cc3m.md">cc3m</a> 3M image/text pairs that can be downloaded in one hour</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/cc12m.md">cc12m</a> 12M image/text pairs that can be downloaded in five hour</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/laion400m.md">laion400m</a> 400M image/text pairs that can be downloaded in 3.5 days</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/laion5B.md">laion5B</a> 5B image/text pairs that can be downloaded in 7 days using 10 nodes</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/laion-aesthetic.md">laion-aesthetic</a> Laion aesthetic is a 120M laion5B subset with aesthetic > 7 pwatermark < 0.8 punsafe < 0.5</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/laion-art.md">laion-art</a> Laion aesthetic is a 8M laion5B subset with aesthetic > 8 pwatermark < 0.8 punsafe < 0.5</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/laion-coco.md">laion-coco</a> Laion-COCO is a 600M subset of LAION2B-EN, captioned with an ensemble of BLIP L/14 and 2 CLIP versions (L/14 and RN50x64).</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/laion-high-resolution.md">laion-high-resolution</a> Laion high resolution is a 170M resolution >= 1024x1024 subset of laion5B</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/laion-face.md">laion-face</a> Laion face is the human face subset of LAION-400M for large-scale face pretraining. It has 50M image-text pairs.</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/coyo-700m.md">coyo-700m</a> COYO is a large-scale dataset that contains 747M image-text pairs as well as many other meta-attributes to increase the usability to train various models.</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/common_pool.md">commonpool</a> CommonPool is a large-scale dataset collected from CommonCrawl containing 12.8B image-text pairs.</li><li><a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/dataset_examples/datacomp.md">datacomp-1b</a> DataComp-1B is a large-scale dataset with 1.4B image-text pairs filtered from CommonPool.</li></ul><p dir="auto">For all these examples, you may want to tweak the resizing to your preferences. The default is 256x256 with white borders.See options below.</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Usage</h2><a id="user-content-usage" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Usage" href="#usage"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">First get some image url list. For example:</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="echo 'https://placekitten.com/200/305' >> myimglist.txtecho 'https://placekitten.com/200/304' >> myimglist.txtecho 'https://placekitten.com/200/303' >> myimglist.txt"><pre><span class="pl-c1">echo</span> <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">'</span>https://placekitten.com/200/305<span class="pl-pds">'</span></span> <span class="pl-k">>></span> myimglist.txt<span class="pl-c1">echo</span> <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">'</span>https://placekitten.com/200/304<span class="pl-pds">'</span></span> <span class="pl-k">>></span> myimglist.txt<span class="pl-c1">echo</span> <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">'</span>https://placekitten.com/200/303<span class="pl-pds">'</span></span> <span class="pl-k">>></span> myimglist.txt</pre></div><p dir="auto">Then, run the tool:</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-shell notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="img2dataset --url_list=myimglist.txt --output_folder=output_folder --thread_count=64 --image_size=256"><pre>img2dataset --url_list=myimglist.txt --output_folder=output_folder --thread_count=64 --image_size=256</pre></div><p dir="auto">The tool will then automatically download the urls, resize them, and store them with that format:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>output_folder<ul dir="auto"><li>00000<ul dir="auto"><li>000000000.jpg</li><li>000000001.jpg</li><li>000000002.jpg</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><p dir="auto">or as this format if choosing webdataset:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>output_folder<ul dir="auto"><li>00000.tar containing:<ul dir="auto"><li>000000000.jpg</li><li>000000001.jpg</li><li>000000002.jpg</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><p dir="auto">with each number being the position in the list. The subfolders avoids having too many files in a single folder.</p><p dir="auto">If <strong>captions</strong> are provided, they will be saved as 0.txt, 1.txt, ...</p><p dir="auto">This can then easily be fed into machine learning training or any other use case.</p><p dir="auto">Also .json files named 0.json, 1.json,... are saved with these keys:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>url</li><li>caption</li><li>key of the form 000010005 : the first 5 digits are the shard id, the last 4 are the index in the shard</li><li>status : whether the download succeeded</li><li>error_message</li><li>width</li><li>height</li><li>original_width</li><li>original_height</li><li>exif</li></ul><p dir="auto">Also a .parquet file will be saved with the same name as the subfolder/tar files containing these same metadata.It can be used to analyze the results efficiently.</p><p dir="auto">.json files will also be saved with the same name suffixed by _stats, they contain stats collected during downloading (download time, number of success, ...)</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Python examples</h2><a id="user-content-python-examples" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Python examples" href="#python-examples"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">This module exposes a single function <code>download</code> which takes the same arguments as the command line tool:</p><ul dir="auto"><li><strong>url_list</strong> A file with the list of url of images to download. It can be a folder of such files. (<em>required</em>)</li><li><strong>image_size</strong> The size to resize image to (default <em>256</em>)</li><li><strong>output_folder</strong> The path to the output folder. (default <em>"images"</em>)</li><li><strong>processes_count</strong> The number of processes used for downloading the pictures. This is important to be high for performance. (default <em>1</em>)</li><li><strong>thread_count</strong> The number of threads used for downloading the pictures. This is important to be high for performance. (default <em>256</em>)</li><li><strong>resize_mode</strong> The way to resize pictures, can be no, border or keep_ratio (default <em>border</em>)<ul dir="auto"><li><strong>no</strong> doesn't resize at all</li><li><strong>border</strong> will make the image image_size x image_size and add a border</li><li><strong>keep_ratio</strong> will keep the ratio and make the smallest side of the picture image_size</li><li><strong>keep_ratio_largest</strong> will keep the ratio and make the largest side of the picture image_size</li><li><strong>center_crop</strong> will keep the ratio and center crop the largest side so the picture is squared</li></ul></li><li><strong>resize_only_if_bigger</strong> resize pictures only if bigger that the image_size (default <em>False</em>)</li><li><strong>upscale_interpolation</strong> kind of upscale interpolation used for resizing (default <em>"lanczos"</em>)</li><li><strong>downscale_interpolation</strong> kind of downscale interpolation used for resizing (default <em>"area"</em>)</li><li><strong>encode_quality</strong> encode quality from 0 to 100, when using png it is the compression factor from 0 to 9 (default <em>95</em>)</li><li><strong>encode_format</strong> encode format (default <em>jpg</em>)<ul dir="auto"><li><strong>jpg</strong> jpeg format</li><li><strong>png</strong> png format</li><li><strong>webp</strong> webp format</li></ul></li><li><strong>skip_reencode</strong> whether to skip reencoding if no resizing is done (default <em>False</em>)</li><li><strong>output_format</strong> decides how to save pictures (default <em>files</em>)<ul dir="auto"><li><strong>files</strong> saves as a set of subfolder containing pictures</li><li><strong>webdataset</strong> saves as tars containing pictures</li><li><strong>parquet</strong> saves as parquet containing pictures as bytes</li><li><strong>tfrecord</strong> saves as tfrecord containing pictures as bytes</li><li><strong>dummy</strong> does not save. Useful for benchmarks</li></ul></li><li><strong>input_format</strong> decides how to load the urls (default <em>txt</em>)<ul dir="auto"><li><strong>txt</strong> loads the urls as a text file of url, one per line</li><li><strong>txt.gz</strong> loads the urls as a compressed (gzip) txt.gz with a list of url, one per line</li><li><strong>csv</strong> loads the urls and optional caption as a csv</li><li><strong>csv.gz</strong> loads the urls and optional caption, as a compressed (gzip) csv.gz</li><li><strong>tsv</strong> loads the urls and optional caption as a tsv</li><li><strong>tsv.gz</strong> loads the urls and optional caption, as a compressed (gzip) tsv.gz</li><li><strong>json</strong> loads the urls and optional caption as a json</li><li><strong>json.gz</strong> loads the urls and optional caption, as a compressed (gzip) json.gz</li><li><strong>jsonl</strong> loads the urls and optional caption as a jsonl. see <a href="https://jsonlines.org/" rel="nofollow">jsonlines</a> for more</li><li><strong>jsonl.gz</strong> loads the urls and optional caption, as a compressed (gzip) jsonl.gz. see <a href="https://jsonlines.org/" rel="nofollow">jsonlines</a> for more</li><li><strong>parquet</strong> loads the urls and optional caption as a parquet</li></ul></li><li><strong>url_col</strong> the name of the url column for parquet and csv (default <em>url</em>)</li><li><strong>caption_col</strong> the name of the caption column for parquet and csv (default <em>None</em>)</li><li><strong>bbox_col</strong> the name of the bounding box column. Bounding boxes are assumed to have format <code>[x_min, y_min, x_max, y_max]</code>, with all elements being floats in <em>[0,1]</em> (relative to the size of the image). If <em>None</em>, then no bounding box blurring is performed (default <em>None</em>)</li><li><strong>number_sample_per_shard</strong> the number of sample that will be downloaded in one shard (default <em>10000</em>)</li><li><strong>extract_exif</strong> if true, extract the exif information of the images and save it to the metadata (default <em>True</em>)</li><li><strong>save_additional_columns</strong> list of additional columns to take from the csv/parquet files and save in metadata files (default <em>None</em>)</li><li><strong>timeout</strong> maximum time (in seconds) to wait when trying to download an image (default <em>10</em>)</li><li><strong>enable_wandb</strong> whether to enable wandb logging (default <em>False</em>)</li><li><strong>wandb_project</strong> name of W&B project used (default <em>img2dataset</em>)</li><li><strong>oom_shard_count</strong> the order of magnitude of the number of shards, used only to decide what zero padding to use to name the shard files (default <em>5</em>)</li><li><strong>compute_hash</strong> the hash of raw images to compute and store in the metadata, one of <em>None</em>, <em>md5</em>, <em>sha256</em>, <em>sha512</em> (default <em>sha256</em>)</li><li><strong>verify_hash</strong> if not <em>None</em>, then this is a list of two elements that will be used to verify hashes based on the provided input. The first element of this list is the label of the column containing the hashes in the input file, while the second one is the type of the hash that is being checked (default <em>None</em>)</li><li><strong>distributor</strong> choose how to distribute the downloading (default <em>multiprocessing</em>)<ul dir="auto"><li><strong>multiprocessing</strong> use a multiprocessing pool to spawn processes</li><li><strong>pyspark</strong> use a pyspark session to create workers on a spark cluster (see details below)</li><li><strong>ray</strong> use a ray cluster. See ray example.</li></ul></li><li><strong>subjob_size</strong> the number of shards to download in each subjob supporting it, a subjob can be a pyspark job for example (default <em>1000</em>)</li><li><strong>retries</strong> number of time a download should be retried (default <em>0</em>)</li><li><strong>disable_all_reencoding</strong> if set to True, this will keep the image files in their original state with no resizing and no conversion, will not even check if the image is valid. Useful for benchmarks. To use only if you plan to post process the images by another program and you have plenty of storage available. (default <em>False</em>)</li><li><strong>min_image_size</strong> minimum size of the image to download (default <em>0</em>)</li><li><strong>max_image_area</strong> maximum area of the image to download (default <em>inf</em>)</li><li><strong>max_aspect_ratio</strong> maximum aspect ratio of the image to download (default <em>inf</em>)</li><li><strong>incremental_mode</strong> Can be "incremental", "overwrite" or "extend". For "incremental", img2dataset will download all the shards that were not downloaded, for "overwrite" img2dataset will delete recursively the output folder then start from zero, for "extend" img2dataset will download shards from the next available shard number (default <em>incremental</em>)</li><li><strong>max_shard_retry</strong> Number of time to retry failed shards at the end (default <em>1</em>)</li><li><strong>user_agent_token</strong> Additional identifying token that will be added to the User-Agent header sent with HTTP requests to download images; for example: "img2downloader". (default <em>None</em>)</li><li><strong>disallowed_header_directives</strong> List of X-Robots-Tags header directives that, if present in HTTP response when downloading an image, will cause the image to be excluded from the output dataset. To ignore x-robots-tags, pass '[]'. (default '["noai", "noimageai", "noindex", "noimageindex"]')</li></ul><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Incremental mode</h2><a dir="auto">Output format choice</h2><a id="user-content-output-format-choice" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Output format choice" href="#output-format-choice"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">Img2dataset support several formats. There are trade off for which to choose:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>files: this is the simplest one, images are simply saved as files. It's good for up to 1M samples on a local file system. Beyond that performance issues appear very fast. Handling more than a million files in standard filesystem does not work well.</li><li>webdataset: webdataset format saves samples in tar files, thanks to <a href="https://webdataset.github.io/webdataset/" rel="nofollow">webdataset</a> library, this makes it possible to load the resulting dataset fast in both pytorch, tensorflow and jax. Choose this for most use cases. It works well for any filesystem</li><li>parquet: parquet is a columnar format that allows fast filtering. It's particularly easy to read it using pyarrow and pyspark. Choose this if the rest of your data ecosystem is based on pyspark. <a href="https://github.com/uber/petastorm">petastorm</a> can be used to read the data but it's not as easy to use as webdataset</li><li>tfrecord: tfrecord is a protobuf based format. It's particularly easy to use from tensorflow and using <a href="https://www.tensorflow.org/guide/data" rel="nofollow">tf data</a>. Use this if you plan to use the dataset only in the tensorflow ecosystem. The tensorflow writer does not use fsspec and as a consequence supports only a limited amount of filesystem, including local, hdfs, s3 and gcs. It is also less efficient than the webdataset writer when writing to other filesystems than local, losing some 30% performance.</li></ul><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" settings.</p><p dir="auto">Here are a few comparisons of space used for 1M images at 256 x 256:</p><table><thead><tr><th>format</th><th>quality</th><th>compression</th><th>size (GB)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>jpg</td><td>100</td><td>N/A</td><td>54.2</td></tr><tr><td>jpg</td><td>95</td><td>N/A</td><td>29.9</td></tr><tr><td>png</td><td>N/A</td><td>0</td><td>187.9</td></tr><tr><td>png</td><td>N/A</td><td>9</td><td>97.7</td></tr><tr><td>webp</td><td>100</td><td>N/A</td><td>31.0</td></tr><tr><td>webp</td><td>95</td><td>N/A</td><td>23.8</td></tr></tbody></table><p dir="auto">Notes:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>jpeg at quality 100 is NOT lossless</li><li>png format is lossless</li><li>webp at quality >100 is lossless (<a href="https://docs.opencv.org/3.4/d8/d6a/group__imgcodecs__flags.html" rel="nofollow">see OpenCV Docs</a>)</li><li>same quality scale between formats does not mean same image quality</li></ul><div pre-filter your dataset prior to downloading.</p><p dir="auto">If needed, you can use:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>--min_image_size SIZE : to filter out images with one side smaller than SIZE</li><li>--max_image_area SIZE : to filter out images with area larger than SIZE</li><li>--max_aspect_ratio RATIO : to filter out images with an aspect ratio greater than RATIO</li></ul><p dir="auto">When filtering data, it is recommended to pre-shuffle your dataset to limit the impact on shard size distribution.</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" automatically drop out the images that do not match theses hashes.In that case you can use <code>--compute_hash "md5" --verify_hash '["md5","md5"]'</code>Some of those images are actually still good but have been slightly changed by the websites.</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">How to tweak the options</h2><a id="user-content-how-to-tweak-the-options" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: How to tweak the options" href="#how-to-tweak-the-options"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">The default values should be good enough for small sized dataset. For larger ones, these tips may help you get the best performance:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>set the processes_count as the number of cores your machine has</li><li>increase thread_count as long as your bandwidth and cpu are below the limits</li><li>I advise to set output_format to webdataset if your dataset has more than 1M elements, it will be easier to manipulate few tars rather than million of files</li><li>keeping metadata to True can be useful to check what items were already saved and avoid redownloading them</li></ul><p dir="auto">To benchmark your system, and img2dataset interactions with it, it may be interesting to enable these options (only for testing, not for real downloads)</p><ul dir="auto"><li>--output_format dummy : will not save anything. Good to remove the storage bottleneck</li><li>--disable_all_reencoding True : will not reencode anything. Good to remove the cpu bottleneckWhen both these options are enabled, the only bottlenecks left are network related: eg dns setup, your bandwidth or the url servers bandwidth.</li></ul><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">File system support</h2><a id="user-content-file-system-support" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: File system support" href="#file-system-support"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">Thanks to <a href="https://filesystem-spec.readthedocs.io/en/latest/" rel="nofollow">fsspec</a>, img2dataset supports reading and writing files in <a href="https://github.com/fsspec/filesystem_spec/blob/6233f315548b512ec379323f762b70764efeb92c/fsspec/registry.py#L87">many file systems</a>.To use it, simply use the prefix of your filesystem before the path. For example <code>hdfs://</code>, <code>s3://</code>, <code>http://</code>, <code>gcs://</code>, <code>ssh://</code> or <code>hf://</code> (includes a <a href="https://huggingface.co/docs/hub/datasets-viewer" rel="nofollow">Dataset Viewer</a>).Some of these file systems require installing an additional package (for example s3fs for s3, gcsfs for gcs, <a href="https://github.com/fsspec/sshfs">fsspec/sshfs</a> for ssh, <a href="https://huggingface.co/docs/huggingface_hub/guides/hf_file_system" rel="nofollow">huggingface_hub</a> for hf).See fsspec doc for all the details.</p><p dir="auto">If you need specific configuration for your filesystem, you may handle this problem by using the <a href="https://filesystem-spec.readthedocs.io/en/latest/features.html#configuration" rel="nofollow">fsspec configuration system</a> that makes it possible to create a file such as <code>.config/fsspec/s3.json</code> and have information in it such as:</p><div class="highlight highlight-source-json notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="{  "s3": {    "client_kwargs": {            "endpoint_url": "https://some_endpoint",            "aws_access_key_id": "your_user",           "aws_secret_access_key": "your_password"    }  }}"><pre>{  <span class="pl-ent">"s3"</span>: {    <span class="pl-ent">"client_kwargs"</span>: {            <span class="pl-ent">"endpoint_url"</span>: <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>https://some_endpoint<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>,            <span class="pl-ent">"aws_access_key_id"</span>: <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>your_user<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>,           <span class="pl-ent">"aws_secret_access_key"</span>: <span class="pl-s"><span class="pl-pds">"</span>your_password<span class="pl-pds">"</span></span>    }  }}</pre></div><p dir="auto">Which may be necessary if using s3 compatible file systems such as <a href="https://min.io/" rel="nofollow">minio</a>. 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">This tool works very well in the current state for up to 100M elements. Future goals include:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>a benchmark for 1B pictures which may require<ul dir="auto"><li>further optimization on the resizing part</li><li>better multi node support</li><li>integrated support for incremental support (only download new elements)</li></ul></li></ul><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Architecture notes</h2><a id="user-content-architecture-notes" class="anchor-element" aria-label="Permalink: Architecture notes" href="#architecture-notes"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m7.775 3.275 1.25-1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 4.95 4.95l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1-4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1 .018-1.042.751.751 0 0 1 1.042-.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l2.5-2.5a2.002 2.002 0 0 0-2.83-2.83l-1.25 1.25a.751.751 0 0 1-1.042-.018.751.751 0 0 1-.018-1.042Zm-4.69 9.64a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 2.83 0l1.25-1.25a.751.751 0 0 1 1.042.018.751.751 0 0 1 .018 1.042l-1.25 1.25a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-4.95-4.95l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 4.95 0 .751.751 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z"></path></svg></a></div><p dir="auto">This tool is designed to download pictures as fast as possible.This put a stress on various kind of resources. Some numbers assuming 1350 image/s:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>Bandwidth: downloading a thousand average image per second requires about 130MB/s</li><li>CPU: resizing one image may take several milliseconds, several thousand per second can use up to 16 cores</li><li>DNS querying: million of urls mean million of domains, default OS setting usually are not enough. Setting up a local bind9 resolver may be required</li><li>Disk: if using resizing, up to 30MB/s write speed is necessary. If not using resizing, up to 130MB/s. Writing in few tar files make it possible to use rotational drives instead of a SSD.</li></ul><p dir="auto">With these information in mind, the design choice was done in this way:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>the list of urls is split in K shards. K is chosen such that a shard has a reasonable size on disk (for example 256MB), by default K = 10000</li><li>N processes are started (using multiprocessing process pool)<ul dir="auto"><li>each process starts M threads. M should be maximized in order to use as much network as possible while keeping cpu usage below 100%.</li><li>each of this thread download 1 image and returns it</li><li>the parent thread handle resizing (which means there is at most N resizing running at once, using up the cores but not more)</li><li>the parent thread saves to a tar file that is different from other process</li></ul></li></ul><p dir="auto">This design make it possible to use the CPU resource efficiently by doing only 1 resize per core, reduce disk overhead by opening 1 file per core, while using the bandwidth resource as much as possible by using M thread per process.</p><p dir="auto">Also see <a href="/rom1504/img2dataset/blob/main/img2dataset/architecture.md">architecture.md</a> for the precise split in python modules.</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">Setting up a high performance dns resolver</h2><a Use cases involve:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>doing inference and indexing to better understand what is in the web (<a href="https://rom1504.github.io/clip-retrieval/" rel="nofollow">https://rom1504.github.io/clip-retrieval/</a> is an example of this)</li><li>training models</li></ul><p dir="auto">Models that can be trained using image/text datasets include:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>CLIP: an image understanding model that allow for example to know whether an image is safe, aesthetic, what animal it contains, ...</li><li>text to image models: generating images based on text</li></ul><p dir="auto">There is a lot of discussions regarding the consequences of text to image models. Some opinions include:</p><ul dir="auto"><li>AI art is democratizing art and letting hundred of millions of people express themselves through art. Making art much more prevalent and unique</li><li>AI models should not be trained on images that creator do not want to share</li></ul><p dir="auto">The opt out directive try to let creators that do not want to share their art not be used for indexing and for training.</p><div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto"><h2 tabindex="-1" class="heading-element" dir="auto">For development</h2><a
